Definition 1. A planar $X$-labelled rooted tree is a planar rooted tree $T$ with no internal vertices having exactly one child, and with a labelling of all vertices fulfilling the following restrictions: - every internal vertex $v$ with $m$ children is labelled by an element $x_{v}\in X_{m}$; - every leaf of $T$ is labelled by a positive integer in such a way that the following two conditions are satisfied: (1) (labelling set condition) the leaf labels are in one-to-one correspondence with the set $[l]=\{1,2,\ldots,l\}$ (where $l$ is the number of leaves of $T$); (2) (local increasing condition) if we temporarily assign to each internal vertex $v$ the smallest of the labels of leaves that are descendants of $v$ in $T$ (thus every vertex of $T$, should it be an internal vertex or a leaf, has an integer assigned to it), then for each internal vertex $i$ the integers assigned to its children increase from the left to the right. Notation: for $i\geq 0$, $l\geq 1$ we denote by $\mathcal{LT}_{i,l}(X)$ the set of planar $X$-labelled rooted trees with $i$ internal vertices and $l$ leaves, $\mathcal{LT}_{l}(X)=\bigcup_{i\geq 0}\mathcal{LT}_{i,l}(X)$ is the set of planar $X$-labelled rooted trees with $l$ leaves, $\mathcal{LT}(X)=\bigcup_{i\geq 0,l\geq 1}\mathcal{LT}_{i,l}(X)$ is the set of all planar $X$-labelled rooted trees. In particular, $\mathcal{LT}_{0,l}(X)$ is non-empty only for $l=1$ (and in that case it consists of exactly one element, a one-vertex tree with no edges), and $\mathcal{LT}_{1}(X)=\mathcal{LT}_{0,1}(X)$ (since every internal vertex has at least two children, hence in the presence of an internal vertex we end up with at least two leaves).
Definition 5. (1) A (non-symmetric) collection is a contravariant functor from the category $\operatorname{Ord}$ to the category $\operatorname{Vect}$. We shall refer to images of individual sets as components of our collection. (2) Let $\mathrsfs{P}$ and $\mathrsfs{Q}$ be two non-symmetric collections. The shuffle composition product of $\mathrsfs{P}$ and $\mathrsfs{Q}$ is the non-symmetric collection $\mathrsfs{P}\circ_{sh}\mathrsfs{Q}$ defined by the formula $(\mathrsfs{P}\circ_{sh}\mathrsfs{Q})(I):=\bigoplus_{k}\mathrsfs{P}(k)\otimes% \left(\bigoplus_{f\colon I\twoheadrightarrow[k]}\mathrsfs{Q}(f^{-1}(1))\otimes% \ldots\otimes\mathrsfs{Q}(f^{-1}(k))\right),$ where the sum is taken over all shuffling surjections $f$, that is surjections for which $\min f^{-1}(i)<\min f^{-1}(j)$ whenever $i<j$. (3) A shuffle operad is a monoid in the category of non-symmetric collections equipped with the shuffle composition product.
Definition 2. A tree $T\in\mathcal{LT}(X)$ is said to contain a tree $P\in\mathcal{LT}(X)$ as a pattern if there exists a subtree $S$ of $T$ for which $P=\operatorname{st}(S)$. Otherwise $T$ is said to avoid $S$.
Definition 3. The growth rate of a set of patterns $\mathrsfs{P}\subset\mathcal{LT}(X)$ is $\limsup_{n\to\infty}\left(\frac{|\mathcal{LT}_{n,\mathrm{no}\text{-}{}{}% \mathrsfs{P}}(X)|}{|\mathcal{LT}_{n}(X)|}\right)^{\frac{1}{n-1}}.$
Definition 3.3. A $c$-point $x\in X(c)$ is a degeneracy of $y\in X(d)$ if there exists $\alpha\colon c\rightarrow d$ in $\mathcal{C}^{-}$ such that $x=X(\alpha)(y)$. Thus, every point is a degeneracy of itself; a point is non-degenerate if and only it is a degeneracy of only itself.
Definition 3.7. A strong pushout in a category $\mathcal{C}$ is a commutative square in $\mathcal{C}$ such that its image under the Yoneda functor $F\colon\mathcal{C}\rightarrow\mathrm{Psh}(\mathcal{C})$ is a pushout square.
Definition 3.2. A $c$-point $x\in X(c)$ is degenerate if there exist $\alpha\colon c\rightarrow d$ in $\mathcal{C}^{-}$ and $y\in X(d)$ such that (1) $(X\alpha)(y)=x$, and (2) $\alpha$ is not an identity map (or equivalently, $\deg(c)>\deg(d)$). A $c$-point $x\in X(c)$ is non-degenerate if it is not degenerate.
Definition 3.5. A Reedy category $\mathcal{C}$ is elegant if (E) for every presheaf $X$ in $\mathrm{Psh}(\mathcal{C})$, every object $c$ in $\mathcal{C}$, and every $c$-point $x\in X(c)$, there exists a unique pair $(\sigma\colon c\rightarrow d$ in $\mathcal{C}^{-}$ and $y\in X_{\mathrm{nd}}(d))$ such that $(X\sigma)(y)=x$.
Definition 2.4. A multi-Reedy category is a small category $\mathcal{C}$ equipped with a wide subcategory $\mathcal{C}^{-}\subseteq\mathcal{C}$, and a wide sub-multicategory $\mathcal{C}^{+}(*)\subseteq\mathcal{C}(*)$, together with a function $\deg\colon{\operatorname{ob}}(\mathcal{C})\rightarrow\mathbb{N}$ such that the following hold: (1) Every multimorphism $\alpha=(\alpha_{s}\colon c\rightarrow d_{s})_{s=1,\dots,m}$ in $\mathcal{C}(*)$ admits a unique factorization of the form $\alpha=\alpha^{+}\alpha^{-}$, where $\alpha^{-}\colon c\rightarrow x$ is a morphism in $\mathcal{C}^{-}$ and $\alpha^{+}\colon x\rightarrow d_{1},\dots,d_{m}$ is a multimorphism in $\mathcal{C}^{+}(*)$. (2) For every multimorphism $\alpha\colon c\rightarrow d_{1},\dots,d_{m}$ in $\mathcal{C}^{+}(*)$ we have $\deg(c)\leq\sum_{i=1}^{m}\deg(d_{i}).$ If $\alpha\colon c\rightarrow d$ is a morphism in $\mathcal{C}^{+}=\mathcal{C}\cap\mathcal{C}^{+}(*)$, then $\deg(c)=\deg(d)$ if and only if $\alpha$ is an identity map. For every morphism $\alpha\colon c\rightarrow d$ in $\mathcal{C}^{-}$, we have $\deg(c)\geq\deg(d)$, with equality if and only if $\alpha$ is an identity map.
Definition 3.1 ([13, VIII.2]). Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a category. (1) An object $\mathbf{0}$ in $\mathcal{C}$ is a zero object if for every object $A$ of $\mathcal{C}$, there are unique morphisms $\mathbf{0}\to A$ and $A\to\mathbf{0}$. (2) If $\mathcal{C}$ has a zero object and $A$ and $B$ are objects in $\mathcal{C}$, then the zero morphism $\mathbf{0}:A\to B$ is the composite of the morphism $A\to\mathbf{0}$ and $\mathbf{0}\to B$. (3) A kernel of a morphism $f:A\to B$ is a morphism $k:K\to A$ such that: (i) $fk=\mathbf{0}$; and (ii) every morphism $h\colon C\to A$ such that $fh=\mathbf{0}$ factors uniquely through $k$, that is, there is a unique morphism $k^{\prime}\colon C\to A$ making the following diagram commutative: $\xymatrix{K\ar[dr]^{k}\ar@/^{1}pc/[drrr]^{\mathbf{0}}&&&\\ &A\ar[rr]^{f}&&B\\ C\ar@{.>}[uu]^{\exists!k^{\prime}}\ar[ur]_{h}\ar@/_{1}pc/[urrr]_{\mathbf{0}}&&&}$ (4) $\mathcal{C}$ is preadditive if for every pair of objects $A$ and $B$ in $\mathcal{C}$, the set $\mathcal{C}(A,B)$ of morphisms from $A$ to $B$ is an abelian group, and the composition $\circ\colon\mathcal{C}(B,C)\times\mathcal{C}(A,B)\to\mathcal{C}(A,C)$ is bilinear for every $A$, $B$, and $C$. (5) $\mathcal{C}$ is additive if it has a zero object, and every two objects in $\mathcal{C}$ have a biproduct.
Definition 5.9. Let $(\mathfrak{g},[\cdot,\cdot]_{\mathfrak{g}},\phi_{\mathfrak{g}})$ be a regular hom-Lie algebra, $\omega\in\wedge^{2}\mathfrak{g}^{*}$ is called a symplectic structure on $\mathfrak{g}$ if • $\omega$ is nondegenerate, i.e. the induced skewsymmetric map $\omega^{\sharp}:\mathfrak{g}\longrightarrow\mathfrak{g}^{*}$, $\langle\omega^{\sharp}(x),y\rangle=\omega(x,y),$ is nondegenerate; • $\omega$ is a 2-hom-cocycle, i.e. we have $\omega\circ\phi_{\mathfrak{g}}=\omega$, and $\mathrm{d}_{T}\omega=0$: $\omega(\phi_{\mathfrak{g}}(x),[y,z]_{\mathfrak{g}})+\omega(\phi_{\mathfrak{g}}% (y),[z,x]_{\mathfrak{g}})+\omega(\phi_{\mathfrak{g}}(z),[x,y]_{\mathfrak{g}})=0.$ $(\mathfrak{g},\omega)$ is called a symplectic hom-Lie algebra if $\omega$ is a symplectic structure on $\mathfrak{g}$.
Proposition-Definition 3.6. A 2-term $HL_{\infty}$-algebra $\mathcal{V}$ consists of the following data: $\bullet$ a complex of vector spaces $V_{1}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{d}}}{{\longrightarrow}}V_{0},$ $\bullet$ bilinear maps $l_{2},:V_{i}\times V_{j}\longrightarrow V_{i+j}$, $\bullet$ two linear transformations $\phi_{0}\in\mathfrak{gl}(V_{0})$ and $\phi_{1}\in\mathfrak{gl}(V_{1})$ satisfying $\phi_{0}\circ\mathrm{d}=\mathrm{d}\circ\phi_{1}$, $\bullet$ a skew-symmetric trilinear map $l_{3}:V_{0}\times V_{0}\times V_{0}\longrightarrow V_{1}$ satisfying $l_{3}\circ\phi_{0}=\phi_{1}\circ l_{3},$ such that for any $w,x,y,z\in V_{0}$ and $m,n\in V_{1}$, the following equalities are satisfied: $\rm(a)$ $l_{2}(x,y)=-l_{2}(y,x),$ $\rm(b)$ $l_{2}(x,m)=-l_{2}(m,x),$ $\rm(c)$ $l_{2}(m,n)=0,$ $\rm(d)$ $\mathrm{d}l_{2}(x,m)=l_{2}(x,\mathrm{d}m),$ $\rm(e)$ $l_{2}(\mathrm{d}m,n)=l_{2}(m,\mathrm{d}n),$ $\rm(f)$ $\phi_{0}(l_{2}(x,y))=l_{2}(\phi_{0}(x),\phi_{0}(y)),$ $\rm(g)$ $\phi_{1}(l_{2}(x,m))=l_{2}(\phi_{0}(x),\phi_{1}(m)),$ $\rm(h)$ $\mathrm{d}l_{3}(x,y,z)=l_{2}(\phi_{0}(x),l_{2}(y,z))+l_{2}(\phi_{0}(y),l_{2}(z% ,x))+l_{2}(\phi_{0}(z),l_{2}(x,y)),$ $\rm(i)$ $\mathrm{d}l_{3}(x,y,\mathrm{d}m)=l_{2}(\phi_{0}(x),l_{2}(y,m))+l_{2}(\phi_{0}(% y),l_{2}(m,x))+l_{2}(\phi_{1}(m),l_{2}(x,y)),$ $\rm(j)$ $\displaystyle l_{3}(l_{2}(w,x),\phi_{0}(y),\phi_{0}(z))+l_{2}(l_{3}(w,x,z),% \phi^{2}_{0}(y))$ $\displaystyle+l_{3}(\phi_{0}(w),l_{2}(x,z),\phi_{0}(y))+l_{3}(l_{2}(w,z),\phi_% {0}(x),\phi_{0}(y))$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle l_{2}(l_{3}(w,x,y),\phi^{2}_{0}(z))+l_{3}(l_{2}(w,y),\phi_{0}(x)% ,\phi_{0}(z))+l_{3}(\phi_{0}(w),l_{2}(x,y),\phi_{0}(z))$ $\displaystyle+l_{2}(\phi^{2}_{0}(w),l_{3}(x,y,z))+l_{2}(l_{3}(w,y,z),\phi^{2}_% {0}(x))+l_{3}(\phi_{0}(w),l_{2}(y,z),\phi_{0}(x)).$
Definition 4.8. The hom-analogue of the string Lie 2-algebra associated to any semisimple involutive hom-Lie algebra $(\mathfrak{g},[\cdot,\cdot]_{\mathfrak{g}},\phi_{\mathfrak{g}})$ is the hom-Lie 2-algebra $(\mathbb{R}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle 0}}{{\longrightarrow}}\mathfrak{g},l_{2},l_% {3}^{B},\phi_{\mathfrak{g}},\rm{Id})$, where $l_{2},~{}l_{3}^{B}$ and $B$ are given by (17), (16) and (18) respectively.
Definition 3.1. A hom-Lie 2-algebra is a 2-vector space $L$ equipped with $\bullet$ a skew-symmetric bilinear functor, the bracket, $[\cdot,\cdot]:L\times L\longrightarrow L$, $\bullet$ a linear functor $\Phi=(\Phi_{0},\Phi_{1}):L\longrightarrow L$ satisfying: $\Phi[\xi,\eta]=[\Phi(\xi),\Phi(\eta)],\quad\forall~{}\xi,\eta\in L.$ $\bullet$ a skew-symmetric trilinear natural isomorphism, the hom-Jacobiator, $J_{x,y,z}:[[x,y],\Phi_{0}(z)]\longrightarrow[\Phi_{0}(x),[y,z]]+[[x,z],\Phi_{0% }(y)],$ satisfying $J_{\Phi_{0}(x),\Phi_{0}(y),\Phi_{0}(z)}=\Phi_{1}J_{x,y,z}$, such that the following hom-Jacobiator identity is satisfied, $\displaystyle J_{[w,x],\Phi_{0}(y),\Phi_{0}(z)}\cdot_{\mathrm{v}}([J_{w,x,z},% \Phi^{2}_{0}(y)]+1)\cdot_{\mathrm{v}}(J_{\Phi_{0}(w),[x,z],\Phi_{0}(y)}+J_{[w,% z],\Phi_{0}(x),\Phi_{0}(y)}+1)$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle[J_{w,x,y},\Phi^{2}_{0}(z)]\cdot_{\mathrm{v}}(J_{[w,y],\Phi_{0}(x% ),\Phi_{0}(z)}+J_{\Phi_{0}(w),[x,y],\Phi_{0}(z)})$ $\displaystyle\cdot_{\mathrm{v}}([\Phi^{2}_{0}(w),J_{x,y,z}]+[J_{w,y,z},\Phi^{2% }_{0}(x)]+1)\cdot_{\mathrm{v}}(1+J_{\Phi_{0}(w),[y,z],\Phi_{0}(x)}),$ or, in terms of a diagram, $\footnotesize{\xymatrix{[[[w,x],\Phi_{0}(y)],\Phi^{2}_{0}(z)]\ar[d]_{[J_{w,x,y% },\Phi^{2}_{0}(z)]}\ar[rr]^{J_{[w,x],\Phi_{0}(y),\Phi_{0}(z)}\qquad\quad}&&[% \Phi_{0}[w,x],[\Phi_{0}(y),\Phi_{0}(z)]]+[[[w,x],\Phi_{0}(z)],\Phi^{2}_{0}(y)]% \ar[d]^{1+[J_{w,x,z},\Phi^{2}_{0}(y)]}\\ ],\Phi^{2}_{0}(z)]+[[[w,y],\Phi_{0}(x)],\Phi^{2}_{0}(z)]\ar[d]^{J_{\Phi_{0}(w)% ,[x,y],\Phi_{0}(z)}+J_{[w,y],\Phi_{0}(x),\Phi_{0}(z)}}&&M\ar[d]^{1+J_{\Phi_{0}% (w),[x,z],\Phi_{0}(y)}+J_{[w,z],\Phi_{0}(x),\Phi_{0}(y)}}\\ P\ar[rr]_{(1+[\Phi^{2}_{0}(w),J_{x,y,z}]+[J_{w,y,z},\Phi^{2}_{0}(x)])\cdot_{% \mathrm{v}}(1+J_{\Phi_{0}(w),[y,z],\Phi_{0}(x)})}&&Q,}}$ where $M,P$ and $Q$ are given by $\displaystyle M$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle[\Phi_{0}[w,x],[\Phi_{0}(y),\Phi_{0}(z)]]+[[\Phi_{0}(w),[x,z]],% \Phi^{2}_{0}(y)]+[[[w,z],\Phi_{0}(x)],\Phi^{2}_{0}(y)];$ $\displaystyle P$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle[\Phi^{2}_{0}(w),[[x,y],\Phi_{0}(z)]]+[[\Phi_{0}(w),\Phi_{0}(z)],% \Phi_{0}[x,y]]$ $\displaystyle+[\Phi_{0}[w,y],[\Phi_{0}(x),\Phi_{0}(z)]]+[[[w,y],\Phi_{0}(z)],% \Phi^{2}_{0}(x)];$ $\displaystyle Q$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle[\Phi_{0}[w,x],[\Phi_{0}(y),\Phi_{0}(z)]]+[\Phi^{2}_{0}(w),[[x,z]% ,\Phi_{0}(y)]]+[[\Phi_{0}(w),\Phi_{0}(y)],\Phi_{0}([x,z])]$ $\displaystyle+[\Phi_{0}([w,z]),[\Phi_{0}(x),\Phi_{0}(y)]]+[[[w,z],\Phi_{0}(y)]% ,\Phi^{2}_{0}(x)].$
Definition 4.3. [4] A quadratic hom-Lie algebra is hom-Lie algebra $(\mathfrak{g},[\cdot,\cdot]_{\mathfrak{g}},\phi_{\mathfrak{g}})$ together with a symmetric nondegenerate bilinear form $B:\mathfrak{g}\times\mathfrak{g}\longrightarrow\mathbb{R}$, such that for any $x,y,z\in\mathfrak{g}$, the following equalities are satisfied: $\displaystyle B([x,y]_{\mathfrak{g}},z)$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle-B([x,z]_{\mathfrak{g}},y),$ $\displaystyle B(\phi_{\mathfrak{g}}(x),y)$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle B(x,\phi_{\mathfrak{g}}(y)).$
Definition 2.4. A representation of the hom-Lie algebra $(\mathfrak{g},[\cdot,\cdot]_{\mathfrak{g}},\phi_{\mathfrak{g}})$ on the vector space $V$ with respect to $A\in\mathfrak{gl}(V)$ is a linear map $\rho_{A}:\mathfrak{g}\longrightarrow\mathfrak{gl}(V)$, such that for any $u,v\in\mathfrak{g}$, the following equalities are satisfied: (i) $\rho_{A}(\phi_{\mathfrak{g}}(u))\circ A=A\circ\rho_{A}(u);$ (ii) $\rho_{A}([u,v]_{\mathfrak{g}})\circ A=\rho_{A}(\phi_{\mathfrak{g}}(u))\circ% \rho_{A}(v)-\rho_{A}(\phi_{\mathfrak{g}}(v))\circ\rho_{A}(u).$
Definition 2.1. [5] A hom-Lie algebra is a triple $(\mathfrak{g},[\cdot,\cdot]_{\mathfrak{g}},\phi_{\mathfrak{g}})$ consisting of a linear space $\mathfrak{g}$, a skew-symmetric bilinear map (bracket) $[\cdot,\cdot]_{\mathfrak{g}}:\wedge^{2}\mathfrak{g}\longrightarrow\mathfrak{g}$ and an algebra morphism $\phi_{\mathfrak{g}}:\mathfrak{g}\longrightarrow\mathfrak{g}$ satisfying $[\phi_{\mathfrak{g}}(u),[v,w]_{\mathfrak{g}}]_{\mathfrak{g}}+[\phi_{\mathfrak{% g}}(v),[w,u]_{\mathfrak{g}}]_{\mathfrak{g}}+[\phi_{\mathfrak{g}}(w),[u,v]_{% \mathfrak{g}}]_{\mathfrak{g}}=0.$ The hom-Lie algebra $(\mathfrak{g},[\cdot,\cdot]_{\mathfrak{g}},\phi_{\mathfrak{g}})$ is said to be regular (involutive), if $\phi_{\mathfrak{g}}$ is nondegenerate (satisfies $\phi_{\mathfrak{g}}^{2}=\rm{Id}$);
Definition 5.1. A crossed module of hom-Lie algebras is a quadruple $((\mathfrak{h},[\cdot,\cdot]_{\mathfrak{h}},\phi_{\mathfrak{h}}),(\mathfrak{g}% ,[\cdot,\cdot]_{\mathfrak{g}},\phi_{\mathfrak{g}}),dt,\varphi)$, where $(\mathfrak{h},[\cdot,\cdot]_{\mathfrak{h}},\phi_{\mathfrak{h}})$ and $(\mathfrak{g},[\cdot,\cdot]_{\mathfrak{g}},\phi_{\mathfrak{g}})$ are hom-Lie algebras, $dt:\mathfrak{h}\longrightarrow\mathfrak{g}$ is a hom-Lie algebra morphism and $\varphi$ is a representation of the hom-Lie algebra $\mathfrak{g}$ on $\mathfrak{h}$, such that $\displaystyle dt(\varphi_{x}(m))$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle[x,dt(m)]_{\mathfrak{g}},$ $\displaystyle\varphi_{dt(m)}(m^{\prime})$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle[m,m^{\prime}]_{\mathfrak{h}}.$
Definition 2.6. [2] A $2$-vector space is a category in the category $\mathrm{Vect}$.
Definition 3.7. Let $\mathcal{V}$ and $\mathcal{V}^{\prime}$ be 2-term $HL_{\infty}$-algebras. A $HL_{\infty}$-morphism $f:\mathcal{V}\longrightarrow\mathcal{V}^{\prime}$ consists of: $\bullet$ a chain map $f:\mathcal{V}\longrightarrow\mathcal{V}^{\prime}$, which consists of linear maps $f_{0}:V_{0}\longrightarrow V_{0}^{\prime}$ and $f_{1}:V_{1}\longrightarrow V_{1}^{\prime}$ satisfying $f_{0}\circ\mathrm{d}=\mathrm{d}^{\prime}\circ f_{1},$ and $f_{0}\circ\phi_{0}=\phi_{0}^{\prime}\circ f_{0},\quad f_{1}\circ\phi_{1}=\phi^% {\prime}_{1}\circ f_{1}.$ $\bullet$ a skew-symmetric bilinear map $f_{2}:V_{0}\times V_{0}\longrightarrow V_{1}^{\prime}$ satisfying $f_{2}(\phi_{0}(x),\phi_{0}(y))=\phi_{1}^{\prime}f_{2}(x,y)$, such that for all $x,y,z\in V_{0}$ and $m,n\in V_{1}$, we have $\bullet$ $\mathrm{d}f_{2}(x,y)=f_{0}(l_{2}(x,y))-l_{2}^{\prime}(f_{0}(x),f_{0}(y)),$ $\bullet$ $f_{2}(x,\mathrm{d}m)=f_{1}(l_{2}(x,m))-l_{2}^{\prime}(f_{0}(x),f_{1}(m)),$ $\bullet$ $\displaystyle l_{2}^{\prime}(f_{2}(x,y),f_{0}(\phi_{0}(z)))+f_{2}(l_{2}(x,y),% \phi_{0}(z))+f_{1}(l_{3}(x,y,z))$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle l_{3}^{\prime}(f_{0}(x),f_{0}(y),f_{0}(z))+l_{2}^{\prime}(f_{0}(% \phi_{0}(x)),f_{2}(y,z))+l_{2}^{\prime}(f_{2}(x,z),f_{0}(\phi_{0}(y)))$ $\displaystyle+f_{2}(\phi_{0}(x),l_{2}(y,z))+f_{2}(l_{2}(x,z),\phi_{0}(y)).$
Definition 3.2. Given hom-Lie 2-algebras $(L,[\cdot,\cdot],\Phi)$ and $(L^{\prime},[\cdot,\cdot]^{\prime},\Phi^{\prime})$, a hom-Lie 2-algebra morphism $F:L\longrightarrow L^{\prime}$ consists of: $\bullet$ a linear functor $(F_{0},F_{1})$ from the underlying 2-vector space of $L$ to that of $L^{\prime}$ such that $\Phi^{\prime}\circ(F_{0},F_{1})=(F_{0},F_{1})\circ\Phi,$ $\bullet$ a skew-symmetric bilinear natural transformation $F_{2}(x,y):[F_{0}(x),F_{0}(y)]^{\prime}\longrightarrow F_{0}([x,y])$ satisfying $F_{2}(\Phi_{0}(x),\Phi_{0}(y))=\Phi_{1}^{\prime}F_{2}(x,y)$, such that the following diagram commutes: $\footnotesize{\xymatrix{[[F_{0}(x),F_{0}(y)]^{\prime},\Phi^{\prime}(F_{0}(z))]% ^{\prime}\ar[d]_{J_{F_{0}(x),F_{0}(y),F_{0}(z)}}\ar[rr]^{\qquad\qquad\qquad[F_% {2}(x,y),1]^{\prime}\quad\qquad\quad}&&[F_{0}[x,y],F_{0}\Phi(z)]^{\prime}\ar[d% ]^{F_{2}([x,y],\Phi(z))}\\ ~{}[\Phi^{\prime}(F_{0}(x)),[F_{0}(y),F_{0}(z)]^{\prime}]^{\prime}+[[F_{0}(x),% F_{0}(z)]^{\prime},\Phi^{\prime}(F_{0}(y))]^{\prime}\ar[d]_{[1,F_{2}(y,z)]^{% \prime}+[F_{2}(x,z),1]^{\prime}}&&F_{0}[[x,y],\Phi(z)]\ar[d]^{F_{1}J_{x,y,z}}% \\ ~{}[F_{0}(\Phi(x)),F_{0}[y,z]]^{\prime}+[F_{0}[x,z],F_{0}(\Phi(y))]^{\prime}% \ar[rr]^{\footnotesize{F_{2}(\Phi(x),[y,z])+F_{2}([x,z],\Phi(y))}}&&% \footnotesize{F_{0}[\Phi(x),[y,z]]+F_{0}[[x,z],\Phi(y)].}}}$
Definition 2.3. A morphism of hom-Lie algebras $f:(\mathfrak{g},[\cdot,\cdot]_{\mathfrak{g}},,\phi_{\mathfrak{g}})% \longrightarrow(\mathfrak{k},[\cdot,\cdot]_{\mathfrak{k}},\phi_{\mathfrak{k}})$ is a linear map $f:\mathfrak{g}\longrightarrow\mathfrak{k}$ such that $\displaystyle f[u,v]_{\mathfrak{g}}$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle[f(u),f(v)]_{\mathfrak{k}},\quad\forall~{}u,v\in\mathfrak{g},$ $\displaystyle f\circ\phi_{\mathfrak{g}}$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle\phi_{\mathfrak{k}}\circ f.$
Definition 3.4. A $HL_{\infty}$-algebra is a graded vector space $V_{\bullet}=\oplus_{i=0}^{\infty}V_{i}$ equipped with • a system $\{l_{k}|1\leq k<\infty\}$ of linear maps $l_{k}:\wedge^{k}V_{\bullet}\longrightarrow V_{\bullet}$ with $deg(l_{k})$ = $k-2$, where the exterior powers are interpreted in the graded sense, i.e. the following relation with Koszul sign “Ksgn” is satisfied: $l_{k}(x_{\sigma(1)},\cdots,x_{\sigma(k)})=\mathrm{sgn}(\sigma)\mathrm{Ksgn}(% \sigma)l_{k}(x_{1},\cdots,x_{k}),\quad\forall\sigma\in S_{k};$ • a system $\{\phi_{k}|1\leq k<\infty\}$ of linear maps $\phi_{k}:V_{k}\rightarrow V_{k}$, such that for any $x_{1}\in V_{s_{1}},\ldots,x_{k}\in V_{s_{k}}$, we have $\phi_{(\sum s_{i})+k-2}(l_{k}(x_{1},\ldots,x_{k}))=l_{k}(\phi_{s_{1}}(x_{1}),% \ldots,\phi_{s_{k}}(x_{k})),$ such that the following generalized form of the Jacobi identity holds for all $0\leq n<\infty$, $\sum\limits_{i+j=n+1}\sum\limits_{\sigma}(-1)^{i(j-1)}\mathrm{sgn}(\sigma)% \mathrm{Ksgn}(\sigma)l_{j}(l_{i}(x_{\sigma(1)},\cdots,x_{\sigma(i)}),\phi_{m_{% i+1}}^{i-1}(x_{\sigma(i+1)}),\cdots,\phi_{m_{n}}^{i-1}(x_{\sigma(n)})=0,$ where $x_{\sigma(i+1)}\in V_{m_{i+1}},\cdots,x_{\sigma(n)}\in V_{m_{n}}$, and the summation is taken over all $(i,n-i)$-unshuffles with $i\geq 1$.
Definition 5.6. A hom-left-symmetric algebra is a triple $(V,\star,\phi)$, where $V$ is a vector space, $\star:V\times V\longrightarrow V$ is a bilinear map, and $\phi\in\mathfrak{gl}(V)$ such that the following equalities are satisfied: $\displaystyle\phi(x\star y)$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle\phi(x)\star\phi(y),$ $\displaystyle\phi(x)\star(y\star z)-(x\star y)\star\phi(z)$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle\phi(y)\star(x\star z)-(y\star x)\star\phi(z).$
Definition 2.18. An object in $\operatorname{Alg}(Pr^{L})$ corresponds to a monoidal $\infty$-category $\mathcal{C}^{\otimes}$ whose underlying category $\mathcal{C}^{\otimes}_{[1]}\simeq\mathcal{C}$ is presentable and the product $\mathcal{C}\times\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{C}$ preserves colimits separately in each variable. We shall call $\operatorname{Alg}(Pr^{L})$ the $\infty$-category of presentable monoidal categories.
Definition 3.8. For a symmetric monoidal $\infty$-category let us denote by $\mathcal{C}^{\omega}$ the full subcategory of $\mathcal{C}$ spanned by compact objects. Let $\mathcal{C}^{fd}$ be the full subcategory spanned by the fully dualizable objects.
Definition 4.4. Given an object $X$ of an $\infty$-category $\mathcal{C}$, let $p_{0}:\underline{\mathsf{B}\operatorname{Aut}_{X}(\mathcal{C})}\to% \operatorname{CAlg}_{R}$ denote the constant co-cartesian fibration. An action of $\mathbb{G}$ on $X$ is a map of co-cartesian fibrations $\xymatrix{\mathsf{B}\mathbb{G}\ar[dr]_{p}\ar[rr]&&\underline{\mathsf{B}% \operatorname{Aut}_{X}(\mathcal{C})}\ar[dl]^{p_{0}}\\ &\operatorname{CAlg}_{R}}$
Definition 2.10. (Coalgebras and comodules) (1) Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a monoidal $\infty$-category. Define $\operatorname{CoAlg}(\mathcal{C})$ to be $\operatorname{Alg}(\mathcal{C}^{op})^{op}$. We refer to this as the $\infty$-category of (coassociative) coalgebra objects in $\mathcal{C}$. (2) Let $\mathcal{M}$ be an $\infty$-category left tensored over a monoidal $\infty$-category $\mathcal{C}$. Define $\operatorname{LComod}(\mathcal{M})$ to be $\operatorname{LMod}(\mathcal{M}^{op})^{op}$. We refer to this as the $\infty$-category of (left) comodule objects of $\mathcal{M}$. There is a map of $\infty$-categories $\operatorname{LComod}(\mathcal{M})\to\operatorname{CoAlg}(\mathcal{C}).$ If $H\in\operatorname{CoAlg}(\mathcal{C})$, then we let $\operatorname{LComod}_{H}(\mathcal{M})$ denote the fiber $\operatorname{LComod}(\mathcal{M})\times_{\operatorname{CoAlg}(\mathcal{C})}\{H\}$. We refer to $\operatorname{LComod}_{H}(\mathcal{M})$ as the $\infty$-category of left $H$-comodules in $\mathcal{M}$. Alternately, $\operatorname{LComod}_{H}(\mathcal{M})\simeq\operatorname{LMod}_{H}(\mathcal{M% }^{op})^{op}$.
Definition 3.1. A derived pre-stack over $R$ is a left fibration of $\infty$-categories $\xymatrix{\mathfrak{X}\ar[d]^{p}\\ \operatorname{CAlg}_{R}}$ Equivalently, via the Grothendieck construction, it can be expressed as a functor $X:\operatorname{CAlg}_{R}\to\mathcal{S}.$ We will denote by $\operatorname{PreSt}_{R}$ the $\infty$-category of derived prestacks over $R$. The Grothendieck construction gives an equivalence $\infty$-categories $\operatorname{PreSt}_{R}\simeq\mathcal{LF}\operatorname{ib}(\operatorname{CAlg% }_{R}).$
Definition 5.2. (Right-adjointability/Beck-Chevalley condition)([5, Def.4.7.5.13]) Given a diagram of $\infty$-categories $\sigma$: $\xymatrix{\mathcal{C}\ar[r]^{G}\ar[d]_{U}&\mathcal{D}\ar[d]^{V}\\ \mathcal{C}^{\prime}\ar[r]^{G^{\prime}}&\mathcal{D}^{\prime}}$ and a specified equivalence $\alpha:G^{\prime}\circ U\simeq V\circ G$. We say $\sigma$ is right adjointable if $G$ and $G^{\prime}$ admit right adjoints $H$ and $H^{\prime}$, and the composition transformation $U\circ H\to H\circ G^{\prime}\circ U\circ H\to^{\alpha}H^{\prime}\circ V\circ G% \circ H\to H^{\prime}\circ V$ is an equivalence.
Definition 2.1. ([4, Def.1.1.2.4]) A simplicial set $K$ is an $\infty$-category if it satisfies the following condition: for any $0<i<n$, any map $f_{0}:\Lambda^{n}_{i}\to K$ admits (possibly non-unique) extension $f:\Delta^{n}\to K$. Here $\Lambda_{i}^{n}\subseteq\Delta$ denotes the $i$-th horn, obtained from the simplex $\Delta^{n}$ by deleting the face opposite the $i$-th vertex.
Definition 4.1. Let $R$ be an $E_{\infty}$-ring. A derived group scheme $\mathbb{G}$ over $R$, is a functor $\mathbb{G}:\operatorname{CAlg}_{R}\to\operatorname{Grp}(\mathcal{S})$ so that the underlying derived prestack $\operatorname{CAlg}_{R}\to\operatorname{Grp}(\mathcal{S})\to\mathcal{S}$ is representable by a derived stack $X$. If $X$ is affine, then $G$ is a derived affine group scheme. Denote by $\operatorname{GrpSch}_{R}$ the $\infty$-category of group schemes over $R$.
Definition 2.14. Given a commutative algebra $A$ in a symmetric monoidal category $\mathcal{C}$, the $\infty$-category of $A$-algebra objects in $\mathcal{C}$ is defined to be the $\infty$-category $\operatorname{Alg}(\operatorname{LMod}_{A}(\mathcal{C}))$. Similarly, the $\infty$-category of commutatitve $A$-algebras in $\mathcal{C}$ defined to be $\operatorname{CAlg}(\operatorname{LMod}_{A}(\mathcal{C}))$. We shall use the notations $\operatorname{Alg}_{A}(\mathcal{C})$ and $\operatorname{CAlg}_{A}(\mathcal{C})$ for these $\infty$-categories.
Definition 3.4. Let $\tau$ be a topology on $\operatorname{CAlg}_{R}^{op}$. A derived prestack over $R$ is a sheaf in the $\tau$-topology if the the associated functor $X\in\operatorname{Fun}(\operatorname{CAlg}_{R},\mathcal{S})$ satisfies the following properties: (1) If $\{A_{i}\}$ is a finite family of objects in $\operatorname{CAlg}_{R}$, then $X(\times_{i}A_{i})\simeq\times_{i}X(A_{i})$ (2) Let $f:A\to B$ be a $\tau$-covering, then $X$ carries the amitsur complex of $f$ to the limit of the associated cosimiplicial diagram. A derived prestack is a derived stack if it is a sheaf for the flat topology.
Definition 5.3. Let $F:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ be a symmetric monoidal map of symmetric monoidal stable $\infty$-categories. Consider the Amitsur cosimplicial complex $C^{\bullet}(\mathcal{C}/\mathcal{D})$ defined by $F$: $\xymatrix{C^{\bullet}(\mathcal{C}/\mathcal{D}):\mathcal{D}\ar@<1ex>[r]\ar@<-1% ex>[r]&\mathcal{D}\otimes_{\mathcal{C}}\mathcal{D}\ar[r]\ar@<2ex>[r]\ar@<-2ex>% [r]&\mathcal{D}\otimes_{\mathcal{C}}\mathcal{D}\otimes_{\mathcal{C}}\mathcal{D% }\ldots}.$ The completion of $\mathcal{C}$ along $\mathcal{D}$ is the limit $\mathcal{C}^{\wedge}_{\mathcal{D}}=\lim C^{\bullet}(\mathcal{C}/\mathcal{D}).$
Definition 2.20. Given a symmetric monoidal presentable $\infty$-category $\mathcal{C}$, the $\infty$-category of algebra objects over $\mathcal{C}$ is the $\infty$-category $\operatorname{Alg}(\operatorname{LMod}_{\mathcal{C}}(Pr^{L}))$. Similarly, the $\infty$-category of commutative algebra objects over $\mathcal{C}$ is given by $\operatorname{CAlg}(\operatorname{LMod}_{\mathcal{C}}(Pr^{L}))$. We shall denote these $\infty$-categories by $\operatorname{Alg}_{\mathcal{C}}$ and $\operatorname{CAlg}_{\mathcal{C}}$ respectively.
Definition 3.9. Let $\mathcal{P}r_{\omega}^{L}$ denote the subcategory of $\mathcal{P}r^{L}$ compactly generated $\infty$-categories and functors that preserve compact objects. We use the notion $\mathcal{P}r_{\omega}^{L,\sigma}$ for the $\infty$-category of compactly generated stable presentable $\infty$-categories.
Definition 2.12. A symmetric monoidal $\infty$-category is a commutative monoid object in $\operatorname{Cat}_{\infty}$.
Definition 4.6. Let $\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}\in\operatorname{CAlg}(\mathcal{P}r^{L,\sigma})$ and let $\mathbb{G}=\operatorname{Spec}H$ be a derived affine group scheme acting on $\mathcal{D}$ via $\mathcal{C}$-algebra maps. Let the noncommutative $\mathbb{G}$-Hopf cobar complex be the following cosimplicial object in $\operatorname{CAlg}(\mathcal{P}r^{L,\sigma})$. $\xymatrix{C^{\bullet}(H;\mathcal{D}):\mathcal{D}\ar@<1ex>[r]\ar@<-1ex>[r]&% \mathcal{D}\otimes\left(H\operatorname{-mod}\right)\ar[r]\ar@<2ex>[r]\ar@<-2ex% >[r]&\mathcal{D}\otimes\left(H\operatorname{-mod}\right)\otimes\left(H% \operatorname{-mod}\right)\ldots}$ Then we say $\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ is a $H$-Galois extension if the canonical maps (1) $\mathcal{C}\to\operatorname{Tot}C^{\bullet}(H;\mathcal{D})$ (2) $\mathcal{D}\otimes_{\mathcal{C}}\mathcal{D}\to\mathcal{D}\otimes H% \operatorname{-mod}$ are equivalences in $\operatorname{CAlg}(\mathcal{P}r^{L,\sigma})$
Definition 2.2. ([4, Chapter 3]) Let $\operatorname{Cat}_{\infty}^{\Delta}$ be the simplicial category whose objects are small $\infty$-categories. Given two $\infty$-categories $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$ define the mapping space $\operatorname{Maps}_{\operatorname{Cat}_{\infty}^{\Delta}}(\mathcal{C},% \mathcal{D})$ to be the maximal Kan complex contained in the $\infty$-category of functors $\operatorname{Fun}(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{D})$. The $\infty$-category $\operatorname{Cat}_{\infty}$ is defined to be the simplicial nerve $N(\operatorname{Cat}_{\infty}^{\Delta})$.
Definition 2.8. The $\infty$-category $\operatorname{Cat}_{\infty}$ is closed under finite limits. A monoidal $\infty$-category is a monoid object in $\operatorname{Cat}_{\infty}$.
Definition 3.6. Let $A$ be an $E_{\infty}$-ring. An $A$-module $M$ is perfect it lies in the smallest $\infty$-subcategory of $A$-mod containing $A$ and closed under finite colimits and retracts. For a derived stack $X$, the $\infty$-category $\operatorname{Perf}(X)$ is the full $\infty$-subcategory of $QC(X)$ spanned by those sheaves $M$ whose pullback $f^{*}(M)$ by any affine $f:U\to X$ is a perfect module.
Definition 2.16. A comodule over a commutative bi-algebra $A$ is an object in $\operatorname{LComod}(\operatorname{LMod}_{A}(\mathcal{C}))$.
Definition 4.3. Given a derived group scheme $\mathbb{G}$ over $R$, the classifying stack is a co-cartesian fibration of $\infty$-categories $\xymatrix{\mathsf{B}\mathbb{G}\ar[d]^{p}\\ \operatorname{CAlg}_{R}}$ which under the Grothendieck construction corresponds to the functor $\operatorname{CAlg}_{R}\to\operatorname{Cat}_{\infty}$ that acts on objects by taking $A$ to the $\infty$-category $\mathsf{B}\mathbb{G}_{A}$.
Definition 2.23. (Comonads and comodules) Given an $\infty$-category $\mathcal{D}$, the $\infty$-category of functors $\hbox{Fun}(\mathcal{D},\mathcal{D})$ is monoidal and $\mathcal{D}$ is left tensored over $\hbox{Fun}(\mathcal{D},\mathcal{D})$. (1) A functor $K\in\hbox{Fun}(\mathcal{D},\mathcal{D})$ is a comonad if $K\in\hbox{CoAlg}(\hbox{Fun}(\mathcal{D},\mathcal{D}))$. (2) There is an $\infty$-category $\hbox{LComod}_{K}(\mathcal{D})$ of comodules over a comonad $K$ in $\mathcal{D}$.
Definition 2.6. (Group objects) Let $\mathcal{C}$ be an $\infty$-category which admits finite limits. A group object in $\mathcal{C}$ is a monoid object satisfying the following property: for every $n$ and every partition $[n]=A\cup B$ for which $A\cap B=\{s\}$, the square $\xymatrix{f([n])\ar[r]\ar[d]&f(A)\ar[d]\\ f(B)\ar[r]&f(\{s\})\\ }$ is a pullback square in $\mathcal{C}$. Denote by $\operatorname{Grp}(\mathcal{C})$ the full subcategory of $\operatorname{Mon}(\mathcal{C})$ spanned by the group objects in $\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 2.21. ([5, Def.1.1.1.9]) An $\infty$-category $\mathcal{C}$ is stable if (1) There is a zero object $0\in\mathcal{C}$ (2) Every morphism in $\mathcal{C}$ has a fiber and a cofiber (3) A triangle in $\mathcal{C}$ is a fiber sequence if and only it is a cofiber sequence
Definition 3.10. Let $\infty$-category $\mathcal{C}\in\mathcal{P}r_{\omega}^{L,\sigma}$. A perfect symmetric monoidal structure on $\mathcal{C}$ is one which distributes over colimits, and such that $\mathcal{C}^{\omega}\simeq\mathcal{C}^{fd}$. Denote by $\mathcal{P}r_{\operatorname{perf}}^{L,\sigma}$, the full subcategory of $\operatorname{CAlg}(\mathcal{P}r^{L,\sigma}_{\omega})$ spanned by perfect symmetric monoidal $\infty$-categories.
Definition 2.13. A commutative algebra in a symmetric monoidal category is a commutative monoid object with respect to the monoidal product in $\mathcal{C}$. This can be formulated as an $\infty$-functor $A:N(\Gamma)\to\mathcal{C}$ where $A(\langle n\rangle)\simeq A(\langle 1\rangle)^{\otimes_{n}}$ and $A(\langle 0\rangle)$ is a final object. The object $A(\langle 1\rangle)$ can be thought of as the underlying algebra object of $A$. The $\infty$-category of commutative algebra objects in $\mathcal{C}$ denoted by $\operatorname{CAlg}(\mathcal{C})$ is the full subcategory of $\operatorname{Fun}(N(\Gamma),\mathcal{C})$ spanned by commuative algebra objects of $\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 5.1. ([7, Def. 8.2.1]) Let $f:A\to B$ be a map of $E_{\infty}$-rings. The Amitsur complex associated with $f$ is a cosimplicial commutative $A$-algebra, $C^{\bullet}(B/A):N(\Delta)\to\operatorname{CAlg}(A\operatorname{-mod})$ with $C^{q}(B/A)=B^{\wedge^{q+1}_{A}}$, coaugmented by $A\rightarrow B=C^{0}(B/A)$. The $i$-th coface map, denoted by $\phi_{1\cdots\hat{i}\cdots q}$, is induced by smashing with $A\rightarrow B$ after the first $i$-copies of $B$ and the $j$-th codegeneracy map is induced by smashing with $B\wedge_{A}B\rightarrow B$ after the first $j$ copies of $B$.
